player.seasonOutlook: Jokic is the reigning NBA Finals MVP, and before that the two-time NBA MVP, but he has been the fantasy basketball MVP for all three of those seasons. He has been the most consistent, unstoppable force in the league, averaging 26.0 PPG, 12.2 RPG, 8.7 APG over the last three campaigns. He increased his distribution last season, coming within two tenths of an assist of averaging a triple-double in truth, and with the way he dominated the postseason it is clear he actually has even a higher gear he can reach when called upon. And remarkably, Jokic is just now reaching his peak prime years at 28 years old...so, despite holding the crown, he still has upside.

Giannis broke the 30-point barrier for the first time last season, averaging 31.1 PPG with his dominant interior game. After spending the last several seasons trying to prove he had 3-point range, Giannis moved more into the paint last season, taking a career-high 17.6 2-point FGA per game but shooting his fewest 3-pointers (2.7 3PA per game) since the 2017-18 season. Giannis may shoot a bit less this season with Damian Lillard in town, but his efficiency and assists could see a bit of a bump. Giannis should be an MVP and fantasy MVP frontrunner again this season, but keep an eye on his availability. He has dealt with knee issues the last couple of seasons, causing him to miss at least 15 games in both campaigns.

Doncic has been a preseason MVP candidate in both the NBA and fantasy hoops for the last several seasons, and this could be the year he fulfills those expectations. Fresh off averaging career-bests of 32.4 PPG on 49.6 FG% to go with 8.6 RPG and 8.0 APG, Doncic is potentially the most potent offensive weapon in the NBA and could be the next to average a triple-double for a full season. Doncic also enters this season with the most talented running mate of his career, as Kyrie Irving's slick offensive game, shooting ability and knack for playing off the ball coul help enhance Doncic's game to even higher levels.

Tatum is coming off the best season of his career in which he topped 30 PPG while setting new career bests of 30.1 PPG, 8.8 RPG, 4.6 APG and 3.2 3PG. Tatum  was able to thrive as the lead in the Celtics' two-star offense, even with Jaylen Brown also notching an All NBA season. Still only 25 years old, Tatum should still be getting better, but he may see a small downtick in scoring with Kristaps Porzingis also now in the mix.

Embiid is the reigning NBA MVP, winning the award after finishing as the runner-up in each of the two previous seasons. Embiid led the NBA in scoring with a career-best 33.5 PPG, and he increased his efficiency by taking the fewest 3-point attempts (3.0 3PA/game) of his career and focusing more on dominating in the paint. The only thing that keeps Embiid from being the fantasy basketball MVP is his injury history: he missed 16 games last season after missing 14 the season before, and those represent the two seasons he has missed the fewest games as a pro. The injury history makes Embiid a bit risky at the very top of the draft, but on a per-game basis he is about as good as anyone in the league.

Haliburton established himself as a top-10 fantasy hoops producer last season, notching new career-best marks of 20.7 PPG, 10.4 APG an 2.9 3PG on excellent percentages with solid steal and rebounding averages as well. Haliburton is beccoming one of the young faces of the NBA, earning an All Star nod at age 23 and playing on Team USA in the FIBA World Cup this offseason. The expectation is that he will continue to develop as the franchise player for the Pacers, and if anything improve on his outstanding numbers this season.

Gilgeous-Alexander was arguably the biggest breakout star of last season, going from a good producer that had battled injury issues in previous seasons to a fantasy hoops MVP candidate and likely first round pick in fantasy hoops drafts this season. He is the clear franchise player for the Thunder, has shown himself capable of producing heavy scoring volume with strong all-around numbers and excellent efficiency. The only risk factor continues to be availability[; SGA played 68 games last season, but has only avearged 53 games played in his last three seasons.

Edwards seems on the verge of making the leap to superstardom. Heis coming off a season where he set new career highs in almost every category,really stepping up his offensive volume with Karl-Anthony Towns injured for several months. Even with Towns back for the playoffs, Edwards exploded to average 31.6 PPG, 5.2 APG, 5.0 RPG, 3.0 3PG, 2.0 BPG and 1.8 SPG. This offseason, Edwards was the clear best player on Team USA at the FIBA World Cup, and just gives every indication that he is about to take over the league this season.

Sabonis is coming off his first full season with the Kings, which corresponded with the third All Star nod of his career. Sabonis led the NBA with 12.3 RPG, and has made himself the best triple-double threat at the pivot outside of Nikola Jokic with a career-best 7.3 APG. Sabonis is the clear top option in the middle for the Kings, and should again flirt with 20 PPG on elite efficiency. Last season's 61.5 FG% represented another career best mark, but it is repeatable on a potent Kings offense with enough perimeter threats to keep opposing defenses off balance.

Entering his 21st NBA season, LeBron still projects as a top 10 fantasy hoops producer on a per-game basis. The thing that now keeps him out of the first round of fantasy drafts is the injury risk of a player that will turn 39 years old in December. LeBron has only averaged 55.6 games in his five seasons with the Lakers, making him a risk to draft in fantasy leagues, but the 27.4 PPG, 8.1 RPG, 8.0 APG, 2.3 3PG, 1.2 SPG and 0.7 BPG he has averaged during that span makes it justifiable to still consider taking the risk.

Curry was as effective as ever on a per-game basis last season, slightly topping his three-year averages to notch 29.4 PPG, 6.3 APG and 4.9 3PG. He even set a new career-best mark in his 14th NBA season, grabbing 6.1 RPG. The risk surrounding Curry is availability. Curry missed 26 games last season, and has missed roughly a third of the Warriors' regular season games in the last six seasons...sitting 157 of a possible 465 games. Curry turns 36 years old in March, and with Chris Paul now a teammate it's possible that Curry gets more rest even in games he plays this season.

Booker is entering his peak NBA years, and will play this season at age 27. He has improved steadily since entering the NBA at 18 years old, and is now a legitimate NBA and fantasy basketball MVP candidate. Even playing next to NBA royalty Kevin Durant and Chris Paul last season, Booker was clearly the best player on the Suns as an effortless scorer and developing playmaker. The playoffs give the best view of Booker's upside playing lead guard next to Durant, and he averaged a whopping 33.7 PPG, 7.2 APG, 4.8 RPG, 2.8 3PG and 1.7 SPG in 11 postseason games. This season, as the full-time point guard with Paul gone and Bradley Beal in the fold, Booker will probably have have slightly less scoring volume but more assists. The only question mark is his availability; he missed 29 games last season and 14 the season before due to injury, but when healthy he is a top-10 fantasy basketball prospect.

Bridges made his name as a 3 and D ironman in his first 4.5 seasons with the Suns, having never missed a game while averaging more than a steal and almost two combined steals and blocks. Last season his trade to the Nets allowed him the unique opportunity to play in 83 games in one season, and also let him demonstrate his excellent scoring potential. In 27 games with the Nets, Bridges averaged 26.1 PPG and 2.5 3PG on 47.5 FG%, making him a budding fantasy basketball star entering this season.

Lillard joins the Milwaukee Bucks after spending his entire career with the Trail Blazers. Dame is coming off the highest scoring season of his career at 32.2 PPG, and even playing alongside Giannis Antetokounmpo shouldn't limit what he does or how many shots he takes. The two are the perfect 1-2 punch, at least on paper. One thing to watch though is whether he can stay healthy; Lillard has 77 missed games during the past two seasons which makes him a risky fantasy draft pick in his typical 10-15 draft slot.

Young is coming off the best campaign of his career as a distributor, dishing 10.2 APG for his first double-digit assist season. This was particularly impressive in a backcourt with another lead guard in Dejounte Murray. On the other hand, Young struggled a bit with his shot, turning in his lowest field goal percentage and 3-point percentages since his rookie season. There have been rumblings that Young and the Hawks have not always been happy with each other, so this could be an important season in determining his future with the team.

Mitchell joined the Cavaliers last season, and the concern from a fantasy perspective was that he would produce lower offensive volume next to Darius Garland and the talented offensive players on his new team. Instead, Mitchell exploded for 28.3 PPG on 48.4 FG%, 3.6 3PG on 38.6 3P% and 86.7 FT%, all of which represented career highs...some to a significant degree. Mitchell enters this season firm in his role as the primary offense generator on a Cavaliers team that hopes to contend, and at 27 years old he should be right at the peak of his prime production years.

Brunson exploded last season, his first with the Knicks and also his first as a full-time starter, obliterating his career-best numbers in almost every category. After playing with Team USA in the FIBA World Cup, Brunson returns this season as the face of the Knicks with expectations to carry the squad. He still has upside, as well, based on his second half of last season: in calendar year 2023, Brunson averaged almost 28 PPG on over 51 percent shooting from the field in a 34 game span even as he battled injury.

Davis signed a super-max extension to stay with the Lakers this offseason, ensuring he remains a franchise playerthrought the LeBron James era and beyond. Davis started full-time at center last season and turned in the best statistical campaign of his tenure with the Lakers on a per-game basis. Davis set new career marks with 12.5 RPG and 56.3 FG% in addition to averaging 25.9 PPG, 2.0 BPG and 1.1 SPG. The issue with Davis is always availability; he has averaged only 48.5 games played during his tenure with the Lakers.

Ball struggled with a repeatedly sprained ankle last season that limited him to only 36 ames, but in those games he continued to develop into one of the elite point guards in the NBA with career best marks of 23.3 PPG, 8.4 APG and 4.0 3PG. Ball is still only 22 years old, is expected to enter this season healthy, and will be playing with more talent in number two overall pick Brandon Miller. Ball still has clear upside, and if healthy could be a top-10 overall fantasy producer this season.

Poole was traded to the Wizards this offseason after playing his formative years with the Splash Brothers in Golden State, and this season he has the opportunity to build his own offensive legacy. Poole's splits the past two seasons give a hint to his upside, with Poole's scoring average going up by more than eight PPG as a starter vs as a reserve. Last season, he averaged 24.6 PPG as a starter, and even when Stephen Curry or Klay Thompson were out Poole still had to try to fit into a cohesive team with championship aspirations. WIth a rebuilding Wizards team lacking firepower, Poole is likely to have the ultimate green light and has the potential to approach 30 PPG.

Markkanen broke out in a huge way in his first season with the Jazz, almost doubling his career scoring average up to 25.6 PPG on his way to his first All Star nod and the NBA Most Improved Player award. The Jazz were expected to rebuild last season after trading both Donovan Mitchell and Rudy Gobert, but Markkanen led them back to challenging for a playoffs spot in his first season. His ability to score at volume and efficiency from both inside (58.5 2P%) and outside (3.0 3PG on 39.1 3P%) make Markkanen difficult for opponents to guard and therefore coveted in fantasy hoops leagues. The biggest concern with Markkanen is health; he has missed double-digit games in all six of his NBA season, and last season's 66 games played was his highest total since his rookie season.

Vucevic's season was almost a carbon copy of his previous campaign; he averaged exactly 17.6 PPG, 11.0 RPG and 3.2 APG in both campaigns. Vucevic did score more efficiently last season, improving in each category with 52.0 FG%, 83.5 FT% and 34.9 3P%, but he dipped in both blocks and steals by 0.3 per game. Vucevic doesn't score quite as much as the third option in Chicago as he did as a primary option for the Magic, but he rarely misses games and is one of the more reliable center options in fantasy hoops.

Fox's game matured last season as he led the surprising Kings back to the playoffs for the first time in a generation. He paired with Domantas Sabonis to give the Kings one of the best big man/guard combos in the league, particularly on offense, where both are primary scorers and distributors. This resulted in the most efficient shooting season of Fox's career, with a huge personal best 51.2 FG%. Fox turns 26 years old in December and is approaching his basketball peak, where his lightning athleticism is merging with experience. He is an easy top-25 fantasy hoops prospect this season.

Durant has been on the very short list of greatest players of his generation, and has been an elite fantasy basketball prospect for the better part of two decades. His per-game production remains absolutely top shelf, with averages of 28.8 PPG, 7.1 RPG, 5.7 APG, 2.1 3PG, 1.2 BPG and 0.8 SPG in the four seasons since he left Golden State. Unfortunately, Durant has only played 137 of the 308 possible games during that stretch due to various injuries, and injury risk doesn't tend to lessen in the second half of a player's 30s. In addition, Durant has ceded the primary option in the offense to teammate Devin Booker, and with Bradley Beal also in the mix Durant's per-game volume could diminish this season as well.

Siakam simultaneously moved to starting center while expanding his perimeter game last season, playing effectively point-center for most of his time on the court before Jakob Poeltl joined the team at the trade deadline. As a primary offensive initiator for the Raptors, Siakam set new career bests in both points (24.2 PPG) and assists (58 APG), while being more efficient at scoring as he's grown into a primary option. After managing only a 45.4 FG% in the first two seasons as the main guy after Kawhi Leonard's departure, Siakam has bounced back with a 48.5 FG% in the past two. In addition to the primary offense, Siakam still provides the 3-and-D value of his early years with averages of 1.2 3PG, 1.1 SPG and 0.6 BPG in that span.

Adebayo is coming off earning his second All Star nod, averaging more than 20 PPG for the first time in his career while maintaining his elite defense an rebounding. He stepped up more on offense in the regular season with Jimmy Butler taking a step back and missing more games due to injury management. Adebayo should continue to progress as a player in his age-26 season as he approaches the peak of his basketball prime.

Irving was traded to the Mavericks midseason, then in the offseason signed an extension to keep him in Dallas for the next few years. This makes Luka Doncic the next superstar forward to pair with Irving, following his previous pairings with Kevin Durant, Jayson Tatum and LeBron James. Irving's ability to knock down jumpers and create offense off the bounce makes him a nice match next to Luka's knack for warping opposing defenses, and with no other bonafide playmakers on the team Irving should get as many shots as he wants this season. The question, as always, is availability. Irving played 60 games last season, tied for the second-most games he has played in a season since 2017-18. He has missed 192 games during that span, making him a per-game monster but risky season-long prospect for fantasy hoops squads.

Murray had a strong scoring campaign last season, playing off Trae Young to set new career marks in field goal percentage and 3PG while averaging more than 20 PPG for the second straight season. On the other hand, Murray's relocation to the Hawks did result in him moving off the ball and thus dropping from 9.2 APG to 6.1. His defensive numbers were also down, with his lowest rebound and steal numbers since his rookie and sophomore campaigns, respectively.

Wembanyama is the most hyped, anticipated NBA draft prospect of his generation. He is widely regarded as the best prospect since LeBron James or Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, if not the greatest of all time. These are extremely lofty expectations for the 7-5 center with 3-point range and an all-court game on offense but elite rim protecting defensive anchor potential at the other end of the court. Wembanyama will likely have growing pains as he adjusts to life on a different continent than his home France, playing against the most physical and talented basketball league in the world as a teenager. He is also playing for Greg Popovich, the coach that invented load management with Tim Duncan and later Kawhi Leonard, so he may not play every night. On the other hand, Popovich also played former number overall pick Tim Duncan heavy minutes as a rookie, so in the games he does play expect to see quite a bit of Wemby-mania.

Banchero is coming off an impressive first season where he earned the Rookie of the Year award. Banchero entered the league with an NBA body, even at only 20 years old, so he seemed to have little difficulty adjusting to the physicality of playing power forward, He was able to create his shot off the face-up at will, particularly against larger opponents, and he assumed the role of primary scorer and secondary facilitator on the Magic. Banchero raised his cache by playing for Team USA during the FIFA World Championships, often playing center, and has all the tools to take a solid step forward in production in his sophomore campaign.

DeRozan had a second straight elite all-around season for the Bulls, though his scoring dropped by 3.4 PPG as he ceded some of his primary scoring role to a healthier Zach LaVine. DeRozan remains effectively a 25/5/5 player with excellent shooting percentages that also turns in a steal and now almost a 3-pointer per game. DeRozan will be entering his 14th season at age 34, but is typically durable with an average of 75 games played per season with the Bulls.

Williamson has some of the best statlines in the NBA over the past three seasons, averaging 26.7 PPG, 7.1 RPG, 4.0 APG, 1.0 SPG and 0.6 BPG while notching a 61.0 FG% on heavy volume. Unfortunately, that production has come in only 90 of a potential 236 games during that span. Williamson is therefore one of the highest risk/highest reward players in fantasy basketball. If he plays the majority of the season he'd be worth a first round pick, but he has only played more than 29 games once in his four NBA seasons, so the risk of using a premium fantasy draft pick on him is extremely high.

Garland followed up his All Star campaign in 2021-22 by nearly matching his numbers despite Donovan Mitchell coming to town and assuming the primary scoring role on the team. Garland maintained a Usage Percentage of 26.9% last season, the second-highest of his career only fractionally below the season before, and has 20-10 point/assist potential on a nightly basis. In addition, at only 23 years old, Garland still has significant upside to increase his production as he endeavors to help take the Cavaliers to the next level.

Porzingis was traded to the Celtics this offseason, marking his fourth NBA squad in the last six seasons. Porzingis is an excellent scoring big, averaging 21.4 PPG in his last five seasons, but he scores more off the face-up and from the 3-point line than on the blocks. He will likely be the third scoring option for the Celtics, behind Jayson Tatum and Jaylen Brown, which could eat into his volume but get him more open looks to improve on his career-best 49.8 FG% last season. The biggest concern with Porzingis is always his availability; he has averaged only 52.8 games/season in the last five campaigns he's played in plus missed 2018-19 entirely. Porzingis missed the FIBA World Cup with plantar fasciitis, but is expected to be back for the start of training camp.

Randle is coming off his best statistical season as a pro, where he averaged a 25/10 double-double in 77 games while picking up his second All Star nod. But, his season did end in disappointment with a late-season injury that continued to affect him into the playoffs. Randolph and new running mate Jalen Brunson play very well off one another, generating easier shots and heavy volume for each. With health, Randle should be in for another big season.

Butler turned in one of his best seasons by per-game average, shooting by-far a career-best 53.9 percent from the field on his way to 22.9 PPG, 5.9 RPG, 5.3 APG and 1.8 SPG. Unfortunately, Butler continues to deal with injury maintenance on his knees that limits his games played. He has averaged only 59.2 games played in the last six seasons, saving his legs so that "Playoffs Jimmy" can explode in the postseason. That pattern is likely to continue moving forward, but since the Heat missed out on the long-rumored Damian Lillard trade and the NBA is set to crack down on load management this season, Butler could play a bit more this season than last.

LaVine started a career-high 77 games in 2022-23, the first time he had played more than 67 games since 2015-16. He entered last season recovering from offseason knee surgery, and got stronger as the campaign went along. After the All Star Break, LaVine averaged 27.0 PPG on 53.2 FG% and took over as the primary scoring option even ahead of DeMar DeRozan. At 28 years old, LaVine should be approaching the peak of his prime and if health permits could be in for the biggest season of his career.

Ingram has quietly ascended to fantasy hoops stardom, coming off a season where he set new career highs of 24.7 PPG and 5.8 APG. Ingram has one of the best midrange games in the NBA, and he emphasized that more while shooting his fewest 3-pointers since the 2018-19 campaign. This resultled in one of the more efficient shooting efforts in Ingram's career, with the second-highest field goal and 3-point percentages and the highest free thrown percentage of his career. If Zion Williamson is healthy enough to play a full season it could eat into Ingram's scoring volume slightly, but he is still getting better at only 26 years old so he still has upside as well.

Jackson broke out with the best campaign of his career last season, winning NBA Defensive Player of the Year while leading the league with 3.0 BPG. Jackson also set new career bests of 18.6 PPG and 6.8 APG, while continuing to be a threat from the outside (1.6 3PG) and supplementing his defensive numbers with 1.0 SPG as well. The biggest concern with Jackson is health; he only played 63 games last season, meaning he's played 63 fewer contests in four of his five NBA seasons and averaged 53.4 games played.

Brown turned in the best season of his career with personal bests of 26.6 PPG, 6.9 RPG and 3.5 APG that earned him an All NBA nod and a historic contract this offseason. Brown has also averaged 2.5 3PG and 1.1 SPG over the last four seasons, strong off-categories that should help him maintain value even if he loses a few shots per game to new teammate Kristaps Porzingis.

Towns was on the short list of potential fantasy hoops MVP candidates just a few seasons ago, but injuries have really taken their toll on his upside. Towns has only played more than 50 games in one of the last four seasons, including only 29 games played last season as he dealt with an injured calf. In addition, the TImberwolves brought in Rudy Gobert to play center last season, which pushed KAT to power forward and ate into his defensive stats (career lows in each of rebounds, blocked shots and steals per game). Simultaneously, Anthony Edwards took over the Timberwolves' offense, which led to KAT posting his lowest scoring average since his rookie season. While still a fantasy impact player, KAT's time as a fantasy MVP candidate seem to be over in Minnesota.

Cunninghtam, the number one overall pick in the 2021 NBA Draft and First Team All Rookie selection in 2022, was well on his way to taking a step forward as a sophomore when injury ended his campaign after 12 games. Cunningham is a lead guard in a forward's body, giving him the versatility to average about 20, 6 and 6 last season with upside to improve solidly in each category moving forward. Cunningham is the franchise centerpiece on a Pistons squad full of young talent and potential, and in his "Magical Year 3", Cunningham could well take a superstar leap into the top-25 of fantasy hoops rankings.

Barnes followed up his Rookie of the Year season with an almost carbon copy sophomore campaign, at least statistically. His scoring, 3-pointers and steals were exactly the same, his assists went up by almost the same amount as his rebounds dropped and his free throw percentage improved while his field goal percentage dropped. But this qualified as a disappointing season after Barnes set the bar with such a great rookie season; most expected him to take a bigger step forward. The stage is set for that leap in Year 3, particularly if new coach Darko Rajakovic gives him more time at the point in an extra-large lineup.

Bane continued his rapid development last season, his third in the NBA, setting new career bests with averages of 21.5 PPG, 5.0 RPG and 4.4 APG. Bane was the top option on offense for large stretches of the season when Ja Morant was out, and that should be good preparation for this season when Morant will miss the ffirst 25 games due to suspension. Bane averaged 24.7 PPG in his first 12 games last season before a toe injury made him miss 17 games and slowed him the rest of the way, but he had a surgical procedure after the season and is expected to be fully healthy to start this season.

Leonard returned for the 2022-23 season after missing the previous with a torn ACL, and turned in a slightly down season by his standards. His 23.8 PPG, 6.5 RPG, 3.9 APG and 1.4 SPG all represented lows during his tenure with the Clippers, and his 30 missed games a high when he's played at all. It typically takes two years to fully recover from ACL surgery, so Leonard should be improved this season. It will be interesting to see if the NBA's increased enforcement of rules meant to limit load management might cause Leonard to play more games; he has typically missed about a quarter of the team's games for load management.

Harden is an enigma wrapped in a mystery going into the season. On one hand, he know what he would look like if locked in and playing with the 76ers: pretty much what he's looked like the last two seasons, when his counting stats were essentially carbon copies. He was slightly better last season than his first in Philadelphia, leading the NBA with 10.7 APG and imrpvoing his shooting efficiency from the field. On the other hand, Harden is embroiled in a very public feud with team president Daryl Morey, stating he will never play for a team that employs Morey. Harden was already risky at this stage in his career due to questions about availability (at least 17 games missed in each of the last three seasons), but this feud/standoff adds a degree of uncertainty that makes it difficult to advise adding him to your fantasy basketball teams.

Murray returned to the NBA last season after missing a year and a half with a torn ACL, and in the regular season he didn't miss a beat. He averaged a caeer best 6.2 APG, and again proved himself one of the better shooter/scorers at point guard in the NBA by averaging at least 20.0 PPG and 2.6 3PG for the second time. And then, the playoffs happened, and Murray absolutely exploded. He averaged 26.1 PPG and 3.0 3PG...again, the second straight time he has achieved those numbers during a postseason run, and if he brings that prowess to the upcoming campaign he has the upside to ascend to a top-20 fantasy hoops producer.

Maxey has improve his scoring and 3-point volume dramatically in each of his first three seasons, and he could be poised to make another big leap this season. Maxey has proven he can be a 20+ PPG scorer, even as the third option on the 76ers, and the drama surrounding James Harden's desire to play for a team without Daryl Morey could potentially promote Maxey to the second option/lead guard role. If that happens, with his speed and shooting ability, Maxey has mid-20s PPG scoring and top-30 fantasy production upside this season.

Jones has spent the last few seasons backing up Ja Morant with the Memphis Grizzlies and when he had the opportunity, he produced. Jones showed his true potential in 22 games as a starter last season, averaging 16.4 PPG, 8.1 APG, 4.0 RPG, 2.0 3PG and 1.8 SPG while shooting 50.0% from the field and 41.5% from behind the arc. Jones has worked on his long range shot, once thought to be a weakness, and has a 37.9 3P% in the last two seasons. In Washington, Jones should get the chance to run the show for the Wizards and carries a top-75 fantasy hoops ranking with top-50 upside.

Dinwiddie returned to the Nets via midseason trade last season, and promptly showed a previously unseen ability to distribute to the tune of a (way) career-high pace of 9.1 APG. Dinwiddie continued to demonstrate his ability to score in the upper teens on a nightly basis but struggled with his shot, notching a 40.4 FG% and 28.9 3P% during those 26 games with the Nets. Dinwiddie enters this season as the clear lead guard, though if Ben Simmons is able to play Dinwiddie could potentially play off the ball a bit more.
